{"id":"2006.11110","submitter":"The CMS Collaboration","authors":"CMS Collaboration","title":"Evidence for top quark production in nucleus-nucleus collisions","comments":"Replaced with the published version. Added the journal reference and\n  the DOI. All the figures and tables can be found at\n  http://cms-results.web.cern.ch/cms-results/public-results/publications/HIN-19-001\n  (CMS Public Pages)","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 125 (2020) 222001","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.125.222001","report-no":"CMS-HIN-19-001, CERN-EP-2020-101","categories":"hep-ex nucl-ex","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Ultrarelativistic heavy ion collisions recreate in the laboratory the\nthermodynamical conditions prevailing in the early universe up to 10$^{-6}$\nseconds, thereby allowing the study of the quark-gluon plasma (QGP), a state of\nquantum chromodynamics (QCD) matter with deconfined partons. The top quark, the\nheaviest elementary particle known, is accessible in nucleus-nucleus collisions\nat the CERN LHC, and constitutes a novel probe of the QGP. Here, we report the\nfirst-ever evidence for the production of top quarks in nucleus-nucleus\ncollisions, using lead-lead collision data at a nucleon-nucleon centre-of-mass\nenergy of 5.02 TeV recorded by the CMS experiment. Two methods are used to\nmeasure the cross section for top quark pair production\n($\\sigma_\\mathrm{t\\bar{t}}$) via the decay into charged leptons (electrons or\nmuons) and bottom quarks. One method relies on the leptonic information alone,\nand the second one exploits, in addition, the presence of bottom quarks. The\nmeasured cross sections, $\\sigma_\\mathrm{t\\bar{t}} = $ 2.54 $^{+0.84}_{-0.74}$\nand 2.03 $^{+0.71}_{-0.64}$ $\\mu$b, respectively, are compatible with\nexpectations from scaled proton-proton data and QCD predictions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 19 Jun 2020 12:51:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 25 Nov 2020 17:28:51 GMT"}],"update_d